<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   What are American shoppers looking for this holiday season?
   ``Decision-making will be based on a new set of criteria
emphasizing old-fashioned quality and contemporary convenience,''
says Robert L. Cohen, vice president of Yankelovich Clancy Shulman,
who monitors consumer trends.
   ``Familiarity and reliability plus value-added extras such as
guarantees are at the top of the list, especially at Christmas,''
he says.
   Several stockings-full of ideas:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Under-$6 gifts for children:
   Scribble Stix are oversized, washable crayons.
   Bow Biters are shoe accessories threaded on to laces to help
keep shoes tied all day.
   Zap Straps are glitter-covered shoelaces.
   And old favorites: Duncan Yo-Yo, Slinky, Silly Putty.
   The ideas comes from Laurie Kellachan, an editor with the trade
magazine Toys and Hobby World, and Diane Cardinale, of the Toy
Manufacturers of America, a trade group.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A suggestion for a gift for women coping with arthritis comes
from a New York maker of fashion apparel and accessories.
   The company, Irwin Taylor, has designed pre-tied bow ties in
which the bow is sewn together so the physically challenged women
don't have to take on the sometimes formidable task of tying knots.
   The adjustable neckband fastens securely and easily with a
Velcro closure and is available in an assortment of colors and
prints.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Egg erasers? Strawberry cake tape measures? Pineapple staplers?
Thumb tack vegetables?
   Office equipment is disguised as food in Li'l Fridge, a
miniature refrigerator filled with office tools from Banning
Enterprises.
   It comes in three colors _ pistachio, strawberry and french
vanilla.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Coca-Cola Christmas bottle, a 6{-ounce glass bottle patented
in 1923 and available until 1937, is being offered for sale once
again, in a limited number beginning mid-November.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The ``hot'' home appliance for Christmas? The automatic electric
bread-maker, according to Beth R. Ellis, senior housewares editor
of HFD, a home furnishings trade newspaper.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A compact road atlas of the United States, Canada and Mexico, is
designed to fit into the car glove compartment, or Christmas
stocking. The Rand McNally atlas is roughly 4-by-9 inches.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A ``Cuddle Up'' heated throw from Sunbeam is promoted as a warm,
cozy answer to Christmas shopping.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid has a new instant camera, Impulse, to record the
holiday memories.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Westhampton Greenery in Westhampton Beach, N.Y., has a
``Birdhouse in the Hamptons,'' a bird shelter-feeder that comes
with a package of birdseed and a pocket-size book of poetry and
prose about birds that sing.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   COME INTO THE BEAUTY PARLOR ...
   Vidal Sassoon hair-styling implements from Helen of Troy Corp.,
at less than $15 each, include an oval-shaped barrel styling iron,
a waving iron that creates deep wavy hairstyles, and a square
crimping iron.
   Holiday packaging of Chaps, Ralph Lauren's men's fragrance
collection, features antique train designs on cigar or see-through
boxes in an effort to capture ``feelings of nostalgia and American
tradition shared at Christmas.''
   Mexicali Musk for Men, from Coty, takes a different approach: It
is packaged with ``Loco Louie,'' a rubber worm wearing a sombrero.
The ``wonder worm'' supposedly holds mystical powers that prove
irresistible to women.
   Perfume remains a popular gift.
   Oscar de la Renta wraps an ounce of perfume in a fur-trimmed
tapestry Christmas stocking.
   Perry Ellis packs an ounce of perfume, 4.2 ounces of eau de
toilette spray and 6.75 ounces of body lotion inside a pinewood
Birdfeeder House.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Thinking jewelry?
   Cultured pearls are available as opera-length necklaces,
chokers, bracelets or earrings, brooches and pins. For men, pearl
studs and matching cuff links.
   Diamond jewelry apparently remains popular. Last year, Americans
bought an estimated 19.8 million pieces of diamond jewelry with a
value of more than $11 billion. Forty percent of those sales were
during the yearend holiday season, according to the American
Diamond Industry Association.
   A Swiss watch called Maple, by Jean d'Eve, operates without a
battery, its energy generated by wrist motion.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   As a possible Christmas gift for fans of the late Andy Warhol,
the National Multiple Sclerosis Society is offering a full-color
limited edition 1989 calendar featuring work from one of his last
projects, his Mercedes-Benz collection.
   The calendar, more than 2 feet high, has monthly panels which
can be removed and framed. The $35 purchase price will be donated
to multiple sclerosis research. To order by phone, call toll free:
1-9-WARHOL.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   For those on your gift list with exotic tastes there is a
reference book advising where to find a suit with free bullet-proof
lining, which hotel room service offers peeled grapes and where to
listen to classical music underwater.
   It's ``Courvoisier's Book of the Best,'' which provides tips on
what it contends are the best travel spots, social and nightlife,
fashion, shopping, culture and food and drink.
</TEXT>
