<DESCRIPT>  GARDEN; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Orchids to you; Are your orchids looking a little sick? In need of TLC? The
Santa Clara Valley Orchid Society will troubleshoot problem orchids and give
potting demonstrations during its annual orchid show and plant sale Friday
through Sunday at Westgate Mall, 1600 Saratoga Ave., San Jose. Show hours are
10 a.m. to 9 p.m. Friday, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Saturday and noon to 5 p.m.
Sunday. Potting demonstrations are scheduled 11 a.m. to 3 p.m. Saturday and 1
to 3 p.m. Sunday. Admission is free.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BEST BET  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  THE WEEKEND GARDENER  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   BEST BUY; Veggies by the pot; To get a jump on spring vegetables, check out
the fresh, new supply of seedlings available in six-packs and 2-inch pots.
Look for tomatoes, squash, peppers and eggplant in six-packs priced from $1;
and in 2-inch pots priced from 50 cents. If you can't plant right away, keep
the plants in a cool location and water every day. They dry quickly in the
tiny pots.;  SOIL; Too wet?; Don't dig in the soil when it is water logged.
How can you tell? Pick up a handful of soil and squeeze it in your fist. If it
sticks together like Silly Putty, it's too wet. But if the soil is loose when
you open your hand, it's OK to dig. Digging in wet, cold ground will compact
the soil and ruin the tilth.;  el,-5 YOUR CHECKLIST; (box) Sow wildflowers in
areas where other plants don't seem to thrive.; (box) Divide and replant
perennials that are crowded or had sparse blooms last season.; (box) This is
the last month to transplant artichokes, asparagus, broccoli, Brussels
sprouts, cabbage, kale and rhubarb. Also plant strawberry, blackberry and
raspberry roots so they will bear fruit this year.; (box) Plant citrus and
avocado trees through May as the weather warms up. A Southwest exposure
protected from the wind is best.;  THE LAST WORD; Water workshops; (box)
Low-water-using lawn alternatives will be discussed at 10 a.m. Saturday at
Emma Prusch Farm Park, 647 S. King Road, San Jose. Fee: $5. Information: (408)
926-5555.; (box) A free class in drip irrigation will be held at 7:30 p.m.
Wednesday at the Urban Farmer Store, 2833 Vincente St., San Francisco.
Information: (415) 661-2204.; (box) How to keep your cool during the water
crisis will be discussed by Callie and Calude McRoskey at 7 p.m. March 28 at
Gamble Garden Center, 1431 Waverley St., Palo Alto. Cost: $15 members, $20
non-members. Information: (415) 329-1356.  </TEXT>
